riants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vienne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Celina, Luc, Philippe, Sylvie.","German: variant of   Venn  .","Dutch: topographic name from Middle Dutch <i>venne</i> ‘water meadow’. In North America, this surname may also be a shortened form of the more common Dutch variants <b>Van der Venne</b> and <b>Van de Venne</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Venn","meanings":["English: variant of   Fenn   in southwestern England, where standard English <i>f</i> is often pronounced as <i>v</i>.","German: topographic name from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>venne</i> ‘pit, moor’, or ‘water meadow’."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde de Vienne was born about 1000, in Turenne, Corrèze, Limousin, France. She married Guillaume de Comborn de Turenne Ier in 1025, in Turenne, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1060, in Comborn, Corrèze, Limousin, France, at the age of 61."},"et":{"um 1000–1060":"umbes 1000–1060","0995–1074":"0995–1074","1020–1060":"1020–1060","1038–1091":"1038–1091","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1091":"1091","1038":"1038","0995":"0995","um 1000":"umbes 1000","1025":"1025","1000":"1000","1020":"1020","1074":"1074","1060":"1060","Thiers, Puy-de-Dome, Auvergne":"Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa","Comborn, Corrèze, Limousin, France":"Comborn, Corrèze, Limousin, Prantsusmaa","Mayenne, France":"Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, Prantsusmaa","Turenne, Corrèze, Limousin, France":"Turenne, Corrèze, Limousin, Prantsusmaa","Turenne, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Turenne, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"um 1000–1060":"noin 1000–1060","0995–1074":"0995–1074","1020–1060":"1020–1060","1038–1091":"1038–1091","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1091":"1091","1038":"1038","0995":"0995","um 1000":"noin 1000","1025":"1025","1000":"1000","1020":"1020","1074":"1074","1060":"1060","Thiers, Puy-de-Dome, Auvergne":"Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, Ranska","Comborn, Corrèze, Limousin, France":"Comborn, Corrèze, Limousin, Ranska","Mayenne, France":"Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, Ranska","Turenne, Corrèze, Limousin, France":"Turenne, Corrèze, Limousin, Ranska","Turenne, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Turenne, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska"},"fr":{"um 1000–1060":"environ 1000–1060","0995–1074":"0995–1074","1020–1060":"1020–1060","1038–1091":"1038–1091","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1091":"1091","1038":"1038